---
description: Services must not access DB; use *.repository.ts with NestJS DI
alwaysApply: true
---

# Service / Repository Layer

Services hold business logic. Repositories hold all database access. Services must not know how the database is designed.

## Services (`*.service.ts`)

- Business logic, orchestration, validation, domain errors.
- **Must not** inject `PrismaService`, import from `.prisma/client-*`, or call Prisma APIs (`findMany`, `$transaction`, etc.).
- Inject repositories via NestJS constructor DI; call domain-named repository methods only.

## Repositories (`*.repository.ts`)

- All Prisma/DB operations. Only layer that imports Prisma types and talks to tables.
- File: `<domain>.repository.ts` in the same module folder as the service.
- Class: `@Injectable()`, `PascalCase` ending in `Repository` (e.g. `PhoneVerificationRepository`).
- Methods: verb + domain intent (`findActiveByPhone`, `markConsumed`) — not raw Prisma API names at call sites.

## NestJS DI

```typescript
@Module({
  imports: [PrismaModule],
  providers: [PhoneVerificationRepository],
  exports: [PhoneVerificationRepository],
})
export class PhoneVerificationModule {}

// service — repository only, no PrismaService
constructor(private readonly phoneVerificationRepo: PhoneVerificationRepository) {}
```

Reference: `backend/apps/booking-service/src/app/outbox/outbox-event.repository.ts`.

## Transactions

- `$transaction` lives in the repository (or a repository method accepts optional `tx`; a coordinating method wraps the transaction).
- Service calls one repository method; does not assemble raw Prisma queries across tables.

## Bad / good

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — Prisma in service
constructor(private readonly prisma: PrismaService) {}
await this.prisma.phoneVerificationCode.findFirst({ where: { ... } });

// ✅ GOOD — repository encapsulates DB; service uses domain methods
async findPending(limit = 100, tx?: Prisma.TransactionClient): Promise<OutboxEvent[]> { ... }
const events = await this.outboxRepository.findPending(50);
```

## Scope

- Applies to all `backend/apps/*` and `backend/libs/*` with services.
- Forward-looking: new code and refactors follow this rule; controllers/gRPC handlers call services only.
